Cloners.

A cloner is a weapon class that makes a copy of whatever entity its bullet hits, instead of (or in addition to) damaging it. There is no separate cloner entity type and no info-file field to set — the cloner behavior is keyed off the weapon's folder name. Any weapon whose folder name in equipments/weapons/<category>/<name>/ starts with the literal word clone is a cloner; cloner, cloner2, clone_red, clone_fast, and clone_silent all count, while a melee weapon that happens to be named cyclone does not. The check is on the leading characters only, not anywhere in the name. Cloners follow every other weapon's rules for damage, range, ammo, fire mode, push, drain, and so on — the only difference is that bullet hits also spawn a duplicate of the hit entity.

What gets cloned.

A bullet from a cloner spawns a copy of the entity it lands on, but only for entity types that the player's weapons can normally damage. The cloneable list is: calendars, clocks, signs, items, walls, staircases, platforms, regular doors, ranged doors, parked vehicles, parked bikes, parked aircraft, security cameras, spikes, projectiles, TTS enemies, and NPCs. Things weapons cannot damage do not clone either: zones of any kind (text, menu, heal, safe, obscurity, bomb, item, npc, projectile), blockages, character or command blockers, switches, audio entities (sound source, sound ambience, timed source, timed ambience, effect space), checkpoints, spawnpoints, travelpoints, hazards, force fields, fires, bombs, mines, time bombs, moving hazards, and vanishing hazards.

Entities that require a destroyable flag to take damage from weapons also require it to be cloneable. A clock or sign placed with destroyable unchecked will not produce a clone when shot, the same way it will not take damage. A vehicle, bike, or aircraft that is currently being driven, ridden, or flown is also not cloneable — only parked ones, matching the same rule that prevents them from being damaged in normal play.

Where the clone lands.

The first cloner shot since the last reset spawns the clone on top of the entity it hit, occupying the same tile. Each subsequent shot spawns the next clone one tile closer to the player along the line between the previous clone and the player. Diagonal positions move one tile on each axis that needs to close. Once a clone reaches the player's own tile, every further shot also lands on the player's tile, piling up there until the cloner resets. The march tracks the previous clone's position, not the position of the bullet's actual impact, so it stays a clean one-tile-per-press progression even after the path between the player and the original is full of clones that intercept new bullets.

For multi-tile entities (walls, staircases, platforms with a footprint, doors, ranged doors, spikes, projectiles with a travel box), the whole footprint shifts as one body — a six-tile wall produces a six-tile wall one tile closer per press, not a single-tile fragment, and a three-by-three-by-five staircase clone is itself a full three-by-three-by-five staircase shifted by the march delta. The clone is a literal copy of the parent's dimensions, not a single-tile impression. Walls and staircases also re-spawn their per-height backing tiles automatically because that is part of how those entities work, so a tall 3d wall cloned once adds a complete column of new walkable surface.

When the march resets.

The cloner counter resets to a fresh start under two conditions: when the player draws a different weapon and re-draws the cloner (any equip of any weapon clears it, even re-equipping the cloner itself), and when the current map reloads (whether through a checkpoint death, a load-map menu pick, or any other reload path that runs the map loader). On reset, the next cloner shot spawns its clone on top of the next hit entity again, restarting the march from that tile. The counter does not reset when the player simply moves to a different position, switches targets mid-sequence, or fires through a different entity type, so the march continues across whatever the bullets land on as long as the cloner stays drawn and the map stays loaded.

Damage and the original.

The cloner's damage field controls what happens to the entity it hits, independent of the clone. With damage set to 0 the original is untouched — no health is subtracted, no break or hurt sound plays, and a single-tile entity like a sign or item is not removed by the hit even though it would normally be. The cloner becomes purely additive. With damage 1 or higher, the entity takes the configured amount the same way any other weapon would, in addition to producing the clone. Multi-tile health-bearing entities like walls, staircases, platforms, doors, vehicles, bikes, aircraft, cameras, spikes, projectiles, and the live combatants take their damage and may be destroyed by repeated hits — that destruction happens through the normal health flow, not the cloner code. The cloner's damage is also affected by the player's per-type damage upgrades from the shop the same way every other weapon is.

Persistence.

Clones live in memory only and never get written to the map's main.sif file. They exist for the current play session of the current map and disappear the next time the map loads — through a checkpoint death, a manual map reload, switching to a different map, or quitting and restarting. This matches the persistence model the /spawn command uses for the same reason: a single play session can produce hundreds of clones, and writing them all to disk would bloat the map file and slow every reload. If you want a placement to be permanent, use /build with the entity's on-disk arguments from the command console or a macro instead.

Inherited properties.

Most entities are cloned with their full stat block intact. Walls and staircases keep their tile, volume, pitch, destroyable flag, transparent flag, and full health bar. Doors keep their open destination, lock mode, password, door id, lock type, automatic flag, ranged flag, speed, all five sound theme strings, and full health. Vehicles, bikes, and aircraft keep their type, speed, fireable flag (vehicles), health bar, and the accel/brake delays where applicable. Cameras keep their vision range, turn direction, turn time, level, and xp. Spikes keep their damage, period, tile, and full z range. Projectiles keep their direction, speed, damage, type, all four behavior flags, stun value, and movement box.

TTS enemies and NPCs are the two entity types with extra inheritance worth knowing about. A cloned TTS enemy is given the exact same SAPI voice, taunt text, hurt text, death text, rate, volume, pitch, attack, defense, fire timing, and weapon as the parent — the clone speaks in the same voice with the same lines and draws the same gun, not a fresh random pick. A cloned NPC keeps the parent's scale level (the value passed in at original spawn time via an NPC zone or a hand-authored map line), so cloning a level-5 zombie produces another level-5 zombie with the same scaled stats, not a level-1 stock zombie. Both clones start at full health regardless of how damaged the parent was when hit — a clone is a fresh enemy, not a wounded one.

Authoring a cloner.

Create a new folder under sounds/decompiled/main/equipments/weapons/<category>/ whose name starts with clone. Put the usual weapon clip set inside the folder's general subfolder (draw.ogg, fire.ogg, hit clips, reload clips if it reloads, and so on) so the weapon sounds like every other one in your pack. Drop a data/info.sif inside the folder with the same set of fields any other weapon uses: damage, fire mode, melee (almost always false for a cloner so bullets fire and find a target), bullet speed, x range, y range, z range, repeat time, spam time, weight, ammo, loaded ammo, max ammo, unlock level, and any of the optional fields like push, drain, scadder, reflection, and so on. None of those fields control the cloner behavior — that is purely automatic from the folder name — but every one of them tunes how the cloner feels to use.

Practical use cases.

A damage-zero cloner is a sandbox tool: spawn waves of NPCs by shooting one example, fill empty rooms with signs or clocks for testing the spire and object info menu, multiply a single parked vehicle into a row, or stack signs at the player's tile to test obscurity zones. A high-damage cloner is closer to an actual weapon — it destroys what it hits and spawns a replacement nearby, so each shot moves the entity one tile toward you while also dealing damage, which can be useful for pulling enemies into a tighter space.

Cloning paired with a scadder weapon is also worth noting. Once the map is full of clones from a cloner sandbox session, a scadder weapon (or any weapon with a non-zero scadder radius) can wipe a whole region in one shot, so a workflow of "clone everything for testing, then scadder it all away to reset" is the intended pattern for stress-testing maps with extreme entity density.

Things the cloner deliberately does not do.

Clones are never written to main.sif and never persist past a map reload. There is no toggle or option to make them permanent — use /build for permanent placement instead. The cloner also does not chain inside a single bullet: each shot produces exactly one clone of the first entity the bullet hits, never multiple clones along the bullet's path. There is no way to make a cloner clone several entities at once with one shot, even with a scadder radius set; the scadder splash damages other entities in the splash zone but does not duplicate them. The cloner cannot copy entities the bullet handler does not see, which means anything in the not-cloneable list above remains uncloneable regardless of how it is configured.
